  "output": "## Test Coverage Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Current state: zero tests.** No `tests/` directory, no `pytest`/`pytest-asyncio` in `requirements.txt`, no `conftest.py`. Every module below is fully untested. `httpx.AsyncClient` is already injectable in `fetchers.py` (explicitly designed for mocking — see its module docstring), so the fetchers are unit-testable without hitting the network via `httpx.MockTransport`.\n\nI'll organize by risk: pure-logic bugs first (cheapest to test, highest bang-for-buck), then I/O-boundary and integration gaps.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — `parse_posted_at` (untested, highest-value target)\n\nUntested branches: empty string, negative epoch, seconds vs. milliseconds epoch boundary (`1_000_000_000_000`), bad ISO string, missing timezone (naive → assumed UTC), trailing `Z`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected_year\", [\n    (\"\", None),\n    (None, None),\n    (\"not-a-date\", None),\n    (\"1643241332430\", 2022),          # ms epoch (13 digits)\n    (\"1643241332\", 2022),             # seconds epoch\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00Z\", 2024),   # trailing Z\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00\", 2024),    # naive -> assumed UTC\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00+05:30\", 2024),  # explicit offset preserved\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at(value, expected_year):\n    dt = parse_posted_at(value)\n    if expected_year is None:\n        assert dt is None\n    else:\n        assert dt.year == expected_year\n        assert dt.tzinfo is not None\n\ndef test_job_key_and_content_hash_stable_across_title_edit():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"A\", url=\"u\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"B\", url=\"u\")\n    assert j1.key == j2.key                    # key survives title change\n    assert j1.content_hash != j2.content_hash   # hash detects it\n\ndef test_job_to_row_drops_raw_adds_key_and_hash():\n    j = Job(source=\"lever\", company=\"x\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\", raw={\"x\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key and row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\nMissing edge case worth flagging as a real gap, not just a test: `n = int(s); if abs(n) >= 1e12: n /= 1000` — a negative epoch string like `\"-1\"` passes `lstrip(\"-\").isdigit()` and is handled, but there's no test proving `datetime.fromtimestamp` doesn't raise on platform-dependent negative timestamps (Windows raises `OSError` here). Worth a test even if you only run on macOS/Linux.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py` — `match` / `filter_jobs` (fully untested)\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef _job(**kw):\n    d = dict(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Staff Engineer\",\n              url=\"u\", location=\"Remote - US\", department=\"Platform\")\n    d.update(kw)\n    return Job(**d)\n\ndef test_include_keyword_word_boundary_no_substring_match():\n    # \"eng\" should NOT match \"Engineer\" — \\b enforces whole-word\n    assert match(_job(), include=[\"eng\"]) is False\n    assert match(_job(), include=[\"Engineer\"]) is True\n\ndef test_exclude_wins_over_include():\n    j = _job(title=\"Senior Staff Engineer - Intern Program\")\n    assert match(j, include=[\"Engineer\"], exclude=[\"Intern\"]) is False\n\ndef test_locations_is_substring_case_insensitive():\n    assert match(_job(location=\"Remote - US\"), locations=[\"us\"]) is True\n    assert match(_job(location=\"Berlin, Germany\"), locations=[\"us\"]) is False\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_unparseable_dates():\n    j = _job(posted_at=\"garbage\")\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is True   # can't confirm stale -> kept\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_confirmed_stale():\n    old = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat()\n    j = _job(posted_at=old)\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=1)\n    assert match(j, cutoff=cutoff) is False\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_builds_cutoff():\n    stale = _job(external_id=\"1\", posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=10)).isoformat())\n    fresh = _job(external_id=\"2\", posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n    out = filter_jobs([stale, fresh], {\"max_age_days\": 5})\n    assert [j.external_id for j in out] == [\"2\"]\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_empty_rules_is_passthrough():\n    jobs = [_job(external_id=\"1\"), _job(external_id=\"2\")]\n    assert filter_jobs(jobs, {}) == jobs\n\ndef test_empty_include_list_is_not_a_filter():\n    # rules.get(\"include_keywords\") == [] is falsy -> matches everything, not nothing\n    assert match(_job(), include=[]) is True\n```\n\nGap worth noting: `re.escape(w)` means keyword lists containing regex metacharacters are treated literally — no test proves that (e.g. `include=[\"C++\"]`). Add one.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` — `Store` (SQLite, currently zero integration tests)\n\nNeeds a `tmp_path`-backed fixture; never point tests at the real `jobs.db`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    s = Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\")\n    yield s\n    s.close()\n\ndef _job(ext_id=\"1\", title=\"Engineer\"):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=ext_id,\n               title=title, url=\"https://x/1\")\n\ndef test_diff_new_job_is_inserted_and_reported_new(store):\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert len(new) == 1 and changed == []\n    assert store.count() == 1\n\ndef test_diff_unchanged_job_is_neither_new_nor_changed(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job()])\n    assert new == [] and changed == []\n\ndef test_diff_content_change_reported_as_changed_not_new(store):\n    store.diff([_job(title=\"Engineer\")])\n    new, changed = store.diff([_job(title=\"Senior Engineer\")])\n    assert new == [] and len(changed) == 1\n\ndef test_diff_updates_last_seen_without_touching_first_seen(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    row1 = store.added_since(\"1970-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")[0]\n    store.diff([_job()])  # unchanged re-see\n    row2 = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE key=?\", (row1[\"key\"],)).fetchone()\n    assert row2[\"first_seen\"] == row1[\"first_seen\"]\n    assert row2[\"last_seen\"] >= row1[\"last_seen\"]\n\ndef test_added_since_excludes_boundary_timestamp(store):\n    store.diff([_job()])\n    ts = store.added_since(\"1970-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")[0][\"first_seen\"]\n    assert store.added_since(ts) == []   # strictly greater-than, not >=\n\ndef test_meta_get_set_roundtrip_and_missing_key(store):\n    assert store.get_meta(\"nope\") is None\n    store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")\n    assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"2026-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_meta_upsert_overwrites(store):\n    store.set_meta(\"k\", \"a\")\n    store.set_meta(\"k\", \"b\")\n    assert store.get_meta(\"k\") == \"b\"\n\ndef test_next_seq_increments_and_persists(store):\n    assert store.next_seq(\"report_seq\") == 1\n    assert store.next_seq(\"report_seq\") == 2\n\ndef test_migrate_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_schema(tmp_path):\n    import sqlite3\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n    conn.executescript(\"\"\"\n        CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n            external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n            employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT);\n        CREATE TABLE meta (k TEXT PRIMARY KEY, v TEXT);\n    \"\"\")\n    conn.close()\n    s = Store(path)  # should not raise\n    assert \"salary_range\" in {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n    s.close()\n\ndef test_context_manager_closes_connection(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"x.db\") as s:\n        pass\n    with pytest.raises(Exception):\n        s.conn.execute(\"SELECT 1\")\n```\n\n**Real gap, not just a missing test:** `next_seq` claims to be safe for \"concurrent parallel pipeline workers\" via `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`, but there is no concurrency test proving that. Given the memory note about [[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]] (shared scratchpad paths already caused silent corruption once), this deserves an actual multi-threaded/multi-process test:\n\n```python\ndef test_next_seq_is_safe_under_concurrent_writers(tmp_path):\n    import threading\n    path = tmp_path / \"concurrent.db\"\n    Store(path).close()  # create schema once\n    results = []\n    def worker():\n        s = Store(path)\n        results.append(s.next_seq(\"report_seq\"))\n        s.close()\n    threads = [threading.Thread(target=worker) for _ in range(20)]\n    [t.start() for t in threads]; [t.join() for t in threads]\n    assert sorted(results) == list(range(1, 21))  # no duplicates, no gaps\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `notify.py` — mostly untested; env-var-gated side effects need mocking\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom notify import _sms_body, notify_slack, notify_webhook, notify_sms, dispatch\n\ndef _job(title=\"Engineer\", company=\"acme\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=company, external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"u\")\n\ndef test_sms_body_truncates_at_limit_and_shows_remainder_count():\n    jobs = [_job(title=f\"J{i}\") for i in range(12)]\n    body = _sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert body.count(\"\\n- \") == 8\n    assert \"+4 more\" in body\n\ndef test_sms_body_is_ascii_only():\n    body = _sms_body([_job(title=\"Café • Engineer\")], [])\n    body.encode(\"ascii\")  # must not raise UnicodeEncodeError\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_webhook_url_unset(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    # should return without attempting an HTTP call\n    notify_slack([_job()], [])  # no network call = no exception, no mock needed\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_no_jobs(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n    notify_slack([], [])  # must not POST with empty payload\n\ndef test_notify_slack_posts_when_configured(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"https://hooks.slack.com/x\")\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"notify.httpx.post\", lambda url, **kw: calls.append((url, kw)))\n    notify_slack([_job()], [])\n    assert len(calls) == 1\n\ndef test_notify_sms_requires_all_four_twilio_vars(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", raising=False)  # missing one\n    notify_sms([_job()], [])  # must be a no-op, not a KeyError\n\ndef test_notify_sms_raises_on_http_error(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"sid\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"tok\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_FROM\", \"+1\")\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"TWILIO_TO\", \"+2\")\n    class FakeResp:\n        def raise_for_status(self): raise Exception(\"bad creds\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"notify.httpx.post\", lambda *a, **kw: FakeResp())\n    with pytest.raises(Exception):\n        notify_sms([_job()], [])\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_notifier_failures(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"smtp down\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"notify.NOTIFIERS\", [boom, lambda n, c: print(\"second ran\")])\n    dispatch([_job()], [])\n    assert \"second ran\" in capsys.readouterr().out  # one failure doesn't block the rest\n```\n\n`dispatch`'s try/except-per-notifier is the single most important behavior in this file (it's what keeps a bad SMTP config from blocking Slack/console) and it currently has zero coverage.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `pipeline.py` — integration test with fetch/notify mocked out\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import AsyncMock, patch\nfrom models import Job\nimport pipeline\n\ndef test_load_config_applies_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n    cfg = pipeline.load_config(cfg_path)\n    assert cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\"\n    assert cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n    assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {}\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_dry_run_does_not_touch_store_or_notify(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: []\\nfilters: {{}}\\ndb: {tmp_path/'j.db'}\\n\")\n    job = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")\n    with patch(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", AsyncMock(return_value=[job])), \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.dispatch\") as mock_dispatch:\n        result = await pipeline.run(cfg_path, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n    mock_dispatch.assert_not_called()\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_persists_and_dispatches(tmp_path):\n    cfg_path = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg_path.write_text(f\"sources: []\\nfilters: {{}}\\ndb: {tmp_path/'j.db'}\\n\")\n    job = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")\n    with patch(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", AsyncMock(return_value=[job])), \\\n         patch(\"pipeline.dispatch\") as mock_dispatch:\n        result = await pipeline.run(cfg_path)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 1, \"new\": 1, \"changed\": 0}\n    mock_dispatch.assert_called_once()\n```\n\nThis end-to-end path (config → fetch → filter → dedup → notify) has no integration test at all today — every stage is tested in isolation above but nothing proves they wire together correctly.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `fetchers.py` — the largest gap by volume (~20 untested parsers + retry/pagination logic)\n\n**Retry wrapper `_request`** — the backbone of every fetcher, zero coverage:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_request.py\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom fetchers import _request\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds():\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(req):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        if calls[\"n\"] < 3:\n            return httpx.Response(503)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    r = await _request(client, \"https://x/test\", retries=4)\n    assert r.status_code == 200 and calls[\"n\"] == 3\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_raises_after_exhausting_retries():\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(lambda r: httpx.Response(500)))\n    with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"failed to fetch\"):\n        await _request(client, \"https://x/test\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_does_not_retry_on_404():\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(req):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        return httpx.Response(404)\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n        await _request(client, \"https://x/test\", retries=4)\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 1  # 404 isn't in the retryable set -> fails fast\n```\n\n**Parsers** — every `parse_*` function is pure and directly testable with fixture dicts; none currently are. Representative template, then the parsers with genuinely tricky logic:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_parsers.py\nfrom fetchers import (parse_greenhouse, parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby,\n                       _amazon_posted_at, parse_amazon, _apple_posted_at,\n                       _apple_hydration, _extract_ds1, parse_google, _ds1_posted_at,\n                       _bd_location, parse_bytedance)\n\ndef test_parse_greenhouse_handles_missing_optional_fields():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"SWE\"}]}  # no location/departments/url\n    jobs = parse_greenhouse(\"acme\", data)\n    assert jobs[0].location == \"\" and jobs[0].department == \"\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_prefers_range_over_description():\n    j = {\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100000, \"max\": 150000, \"currency\": \"USD\"},\n         \"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"fallback text\"}\n    assert _lever_salary(j) == \"USD 100,000–150,000\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_falls_back_when_range_missing():\n    assert _lever_salary({\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"DOE\"}) == \"DOE\"\n    assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_ashby_skips_unlisted_jobs():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"Visible\", \"isListed\": True},\n                      {\"id\": \"2\", \"title\": \"Hidden\", \"isListed\": False}]}\n    jobs = parse_ashby(\"acme\", data)\n    assert [j.external_id for j in jobs] == [\"1\"]\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_parses_us_format():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_handles_garbage():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"not a date\") == \"\"\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"\") == \"\"\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_truncates_nanoseconds_to_microseconds():\n    # raw value has 9 fractional digits; fromisoformat only accepts up to 6\n    result = _apple_posted_at(\"2026-01-15T10:00:03.812668311Z\")\n    from datetime import datetime\n    datetime.fromisoformat(result)  # must not raise\n\ndef test_apple_posted_at_handles_no_fraction():\n    assert _apple_posted_at(\"2026-01-15T10:00:03Z\") == \"2026-01-15T10:00:03+00:00\"\n\ndef test_apple_hydration_returns_none_on_missing_marker():\n    assert _apple_hydration(\"<html>no data here</html>\") is None\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_handles_malformed_json_gracefully():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', data:[not valid json here], sideChannel\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []  # must not raise\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_prefers_create_time_over_update():\n    job = [None]*13 + [[1700000000]]  # index 12 = create time\n    result = _ds1_posted_at(job)\n    assert \"2023\" in result or \"2024\" in result  # sanity check on epoch decode\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_returns_empty_when_all_indices_missing():\n    assert _ds1_posted_at([1, 2]) == \"\"\n\ndef test_bd_location_walks_parent_chain():\n    city = {\"en_name\": \"Shenzhen\", \"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"Guangdong\",\n             \"parent\": {\"en_name\": \"China\", \"parent\": None}}}\n    assert _bd_location(city) == \"Shenzhen, Guangdong, China\"\n\ndef test_bd_location_handles_none():\n    assert _bd_location(None) == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_google_skips_entries_with_falsy_first_element():\n    jobs_raw = [[None, \"title\"], [\"123\", \"Real Job\"]]\n    jobs = parse_google(\"google\", jobs_raw)\n    assert len(jobs) == 1 and jobs[0].external_id == \"123\"\n```\n\n**Pagination loop-termination logic** — every paginated fetcher (`fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`, `fetch_apple`, `fetch_eightfold`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_bytedance`, `fetch_workday`) shares the same \"stop when a page returns nothing new\" pattern — none are tested for the boundary cases that pattern is fragile to:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_pagination.py\nimport httpx, pytest\nfrom fetchers import fetch_optiver\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_optiver_stops_at_max_pages_not_infinite_loop():\n    # server always returns the SAME items -> \"fresh\" would be empty every time\n    # after page 1, so this also exercises the empty-first-page case\n    def handler(req):\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"items\": []})\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    jobs = await fetch_optiver(client, {\"company\": \"optiver\", \"max_pages\": 3})\n    assert jobs == []\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_optiver_dedupes_across_pages_by_external_id():\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(req):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        if calls[\"n\"] == 1:\n            return httpx.Response(200, json={\"items\": [{\"href\": \"/join-us/jobs/a\", \"title\": \"A\"}]})\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"items\": []})\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    jobs = await fetch_optiver(client, {\"company\": \"optiver\"})\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n```\n\n**`fetch_all`** — the concurrency/error-isolation contract has no test:\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_per_source_failures(monkeypatch):\n    from fetchers import fetch_all\n    async def ok(client, source): return [object()]\n    async def fail(client, source): raise RuntimeError(\"boom\")\n    monkeypatch.setitem(__import__(\"fetchers\").FETCHERS, \"ok_ats\", ok)\n    monkeypatch.setitem(__import__(\"fetchers\").FETCHERS, \"fail_ats\", fail)\n    jobs = await fetch_all([{\"ats\": \"ok_ats\"}, {\"ats\": \"fail_ats\"}])\n    assert len(jobs) == 1  # one source failing doesn't drop the other's results\n\ndef test_fetch_source_raises_on_unknown_ats():\n    import asyncio\n    from fetchers import fetch_source\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        asyncio.run(fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"not-a-real-ats\"}))\n```\n\n**Meta's GraphQL error surfacing** is a distinctive gap: `fetch_meta` strips a `for (;;);` XSSI prefix and raises `RuntimeError` on a `data.get(\"errors\")` response (this is literally the failure mode the memory note [[meta-careers-fetcher]] says to watch for when the doc_id rotates) — currently untested:\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_meta_strips_xssi_prefix_and_parses(monkeypatch):\n    # mock _get_text for the page scrape, then the graphql POST\n    ...\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_meta_raises_readable_error_on_graphql_errors(monkeypatch):\n    # simulate {\"errors\":[{\"message\":\"...\"}]}  -> assert RuntimeError message\n    # is exactly what you'd need to diagnose a rotated doc_id\n    ...\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py` — CLI subcommands, entirely untested\n\n**`_normalize_ats`** is pure and high-value (ATS-safe PDF rendering — a subtle bug here silently corrupts every generated CV/cover letter):\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent_normalize.py\nfrom agent import _normalize_ats\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_replaces_smart_quotes_and_dashes():\n    html = \"<p>“Hello” — world…</p>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert '\"Hello\" - world...' in out\n    assert counts[\"smart-double-quote\"] == 2\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_does_not_touch_style_block():\n    html = \"<style>.x{content:'\\u2014'}</style><p>\\u2014</p>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert \"\\u2014\" in out.split(\"</style>\")[0]   # untouched inside <style>\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1                  # only the <p> one counted\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_does_not_touch_script_block():\n    html = \"<script>var x='\\u2022';</script><p>\\u2022</p>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert counts[\"bullet\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_does_not_touch_tag_attributes():\n    html = '<a title=\"em—dash\">text\\u2014here</a>'\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert 'title=\"em—dash\"' in out       # attribute value untouched\n    assert \"text-here\" in out             # body text fixed\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_no_replacements_needed_gives_empty_counts():\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(\"<p>plain ascii text</p>\")\n    assert counts == {}\n```\n\n**`cmd_db_new` / `cmd_db_mark`** — the posted-date filtering and group-boundary truncation logic is intricate and completely untested:\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent_db_new.py\nimport json, pytest\nfrom store import Store\nfrom models import Job\nfrom agent import cmd_db_new, cmd_db_mark\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef sources_yaml(tmp_path):\n    db = tmp_path / \"jobs.db\"\n    cfg = tmp_path / \"sources.yaml\"\n    cfg.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {db}\\n\")\n    return cfg, db\n\ndef test_db_new_first_run_uses_since_days_window(sources_yaml, capsys):\n    cfg, db = sources_yaml\n    with Store(db) as s:\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\")])\n    cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--since-days\", \"7\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"first_run\"] is True and out[\"count\"] == 1\n\ndef test_db_new_dated_only_drops_undated_rows(sources_yaml, capsys):\n    cfg, db = sources_yaml\n    with Store(db) as s:\n        s.diff([Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"T\", url=\"u\", posted_at=\"\")])\n    cmd_db_new([\"-c\", str(cfg), \"--dated-only\"])\n    out = json.loads(capsys.readouterr().out)\n    assert out[\"count\"] == 0 and out[\"undated_dropped\"] == 1\n\ndef test_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary_not_mid_group(sources_yaml, capsys):\n    # two jobs sharing one first_seen timestamp must never be split by --limit\n    ...\n\ndef test_db_mark_rejects_non_iso_watermark(sources_yaml, capsys):\n    cfg, db = sources_yaml\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([str(cfg).replace(\"sources.yaml\", \"not-a-date\"), \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    # actually: watermark is positional, adjust call accordingly\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(sources_yaml):\n    cfg, _ = sources_yaml\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_db_mark_now_sets_current_timestamp(sources_yaml):\n    cfg, db = sources_yaml\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"--now\", \"-c\", str(cfg)])\n    assert rc == 0\n    with Store(db) as s:\n        assert s.get_meta(\"last_scan\") is not None\n```\n\n**`cmd_pdf_render`** touches the filesystem and shells out to Chrome — needs `subprocess.run` mocked for the failure path (no Chrome found / render produces non-PDF output), which is currently the only error path in the file with zero coverage:\n\n```python\ndef test_pdf_render_missing_input_file_returns_2(tmp_path, capsys):\n    from agent import cmd_pdf_render\n    rc = cmd_pdf_render([str(tmp_path / \"nope.html\")])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_pdf_render_reports_failure_when_output_is_not_pdf(tmp_path, monkeypatch, capsys):\n    from agent import cmd_pdf_render\n    src = tmp_path / \"in.html\"\n    src.write_text(\"<html></html>\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"agent._chrome_bin\", lambda: \"/bin/true\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"agent.subprocess.run\",\n        lambda *a, **kw: type(\"R\", (), {\"stderr\": \"chrome crashed\", \"returncode\": 1})())\n    rc = cmd_pdf_render([str(src)])\n    assert rc == 1\n```\n\n**`main()` argument routing** — the mode-word/flag-splitting logic (`-i`/`--interactive` stripped out, mode words end at first `-`-prefixed token) has no test proving `agent.py scan --dry-run` routes `[\"scan\"]` as mode words and `[\"--dry-run\"]` as passthrough:\n\n```python\ndef test_main_splits_mode_words_from_flags(monkeypatch):\n    captured = {}\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"agent.run_claude\", lambda mode, interactive, extra: captured.update(\n        mode=mode, interactive=interactive, extra=extra) or 0)\n    import agent\n    agent.main.__wrapped__ if False else None  # (invoke via sys.argv patch instead)\n```\n(This one is easiest tested by patching `sys.argv` and asserting on `run_claude`'s captured args — worth writing once the harness above exists.)\n\n---\n\n### Summary of gaps by priority\n\n| Priority | Area | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| **P0** | `filters.match`/`filter_jobs` | Core business logic, silent-wrong-answer risk (e.g. empty `include_keywords: []` matching everything, not nothing) |\n| **P0** | `store.py` diff/dedup + concurrent `next_seq` | Data-integrity bugs here corrupt `jobs.db` silently; memory already flags a prior parallel-worker collision incident |\n| **P0** | `notify.dispatch` per-notifier isolation | One misconfigured notifier (bad SMTP creds) must not silently kill SMS/Slack |\n| **P1** | `models.parse_posted_at` epoch/ISO branches | Feeds the recency filter directly; wrong parse = jobs silently dropped or kept |\n| **P1** | `agent._normalize_ats` | Silently corrupts every rendered PDF if a replacement rule leaks into `<style>`/attributes |\n| **P1** | `fetchers._request` retry/backoff | Every fetcher depends on it; untested retry-vs-fail-fast boundary (429/5xx vs 404) |\n| **P2** | Individual `parse_*` functions (20+) | High volume, each cheap to test, currently 0% covered; bugs here mean silently missing/malformed jobs per-ATS |\n| **P2** | `pipeline.run` end-to-end wiring | No integration test proves config→fetch→filter→dedup→notify actually connects |\n| **P3** | `agent.cmd_db_new` group-truncation logic | Subtle invariant (\"never split a first_seen group\") with no proof it holds |\n| **P3** | `fetch_all` per-source error isolation | One ATS 500ing shouldn't zero out the whole run — untested |\n\n**Setup gap:** add `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, and `respx` (or use `httpx.MockTransport` directly, no new dep needed) to `requirements.txt`/a `requirements-dev.txt`, plus a `pytest.ini` with `asyncio_mode = auto` — none of this exists yet, so even the skeletons above won't run without it.\n",
