        "title": "tests/test_models.py",
        "content": "import pytest\nfrom datetime import timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected_year\", [\n    (\"\", None),\n    (None, None),\n    (\"not-a-date\", None),\n    (\"1643241332430\", 2022),          # ms epoch (13 digits)\n    (\"1643241332\", 2022),             # seconds epoch\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00Z\", 2024),   # trailing Z\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00\", 2024),    # naive -> assumed UTC\n    (\"2024-01-15T10:00:00+05:30\", 2024),  # explicit offset preserved\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at(value, expected_year):\n    dt = parse_posted_at(value)\n    if expected_year is None:\n        assert dt is None\n    else:\n        assert dt.year == expected_year\n        assert dt.tzinfo is not None\n\ndef test_job_key_and_content_hash_stable_across_title_edit():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"A\", url=\"u\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"B\", url=\"u\")\n    assert j1.key == j2.key                    # key survives title change\n    assert j1.content_hash != j2.content_hash   # hash detects it\n\ndef test_job_to_row_drops_raw_adds_key_and_hash():\n    j = Job(source=\"lever\", company=\"x\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\", raw={\"x\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key and row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\nMissing edge case worth flagging as a real gap, not just a test: `n = int(s); if abs(n) >= 1e12: n /= 1000` — a negative epoch string like `\"-1\"` passes `lstrip(\"-\").isdigit()` and is handled, but there's no test proving `datetime.fromtimestamp` doesn't raise on platform-dependent negative timestamps (Windows raises `OSError` here). Worth a test even if you only run on macOS/Linux.\n\n---\n\n",
